issue(id="0001" status="closed")
  title Get Docker working reliably in scrubs guests
  user-story
    as-a scrubs VM user
    i-want Docker-backed guests to start, stop, and re-bootstrap without losing Docker usability
    so-that I can rely on Docker-enabled scrubs environments for iterative project work instead of rebuilding them after lifecycle events
  premise.
    A reusable Docker guest shim now exists and is shared by `systemd-ts`. The
    scrubs bootstrap flow now preserves project shim import paths, avoids the
    Lima boot scripts that mutate immutable NixOS `/etc` state, keeps
    non-interactive bash sessions free of scrubs shell startup hooks, and
    handles repeat bootstraps by staging the next generation for boot and
    restarting the guest. Validation on May 28, 2026 succeeded on both a
    generic Docker guest and a guest using the `systemd-ts` shim. The ordered
    lifecycle proof on `docker-lifecycle` completed as bootstrap, shutdown,
    startup, re-bootstrap, shutdown, and startup, and the guest still finished
    with a healthy `limactl shell` session and a successful `docker run --rm
    hello-world`. A separate `systemd-ts-smoke` guest using the real
    `systemd-ts` shim also completed repeat bootstrap plus a later
    shutdown/startup with Docker still working through `limactl shell`. The
    Lima boot-script sanitize path now uses the stable `/mnt/lima-cidata`
    mount path instead of direct `LIMA_CIDATA_*` references, and `bootstrap.nu`
    refreshes existing instance `~/.lima/&lt;instance&gt;/lima.yaml` files so
    older guests can pick up the quieter host-side config on their next
    bootstrap without delete-and-recreate.
  acceptance-criteria
    criterion Docker can be used on the guest to create and run containers successfully.
    criterion A reusable Docker-focused guest shim exists and can be used by Docker-dependent guests such as `systemd-ts`.
    criterion Guests using the Docker shim remain usable across the standard lifecycle: bootstrap, shutdown, startup, re-bootstrap, shutdown, and startup.
    criterion After that lifecycle, Lima SSH readiness succeeds and `limactl shell &lt;instance&gt;` remains functional.
  review-items
    item(status="covered").
      A fresh guest without any Docker shim was exercised through the same
      ordered lifecycle on May 28, 2026: bootstrap, shutdown, startup,
      re-bootstrap, shutdown, and startup. The guest remained reachable
      through `limactl shell`, and `docker` was absent as expected on the
      non-Docker path.
    item(status="covered").
      The Lima boot-script sanitize path no longer embeds `LIMA_CIDATA_*`
      references in scrubs-managed instance configs. On May 28, 2026, a fresh
      `cidata-clean` guest validated cleanly with `limactl validate` and
      completed bootstrap, shutdown, startup, re-bootstrap, shutdown, and
      startup while `limactl shell cidata-clean -- true` stayed quiet. An
      older `nondocker-lifecycle` guest with the previous noisy host config
      was then refreshed in place by `just bootstrap nondocker-lifecycle`,
      after which its `~/.lima/nondocker-lifecycle/lima.yaml` no longer
      contained `LIMA_CIDATA` and `limactl shell nondocker-lifecycle -- true`
      was also quiet.

